      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Max M. Kampelman's proposal (letter, Oct. 11) that we take a six-month recess in Middle East peace negotiations makes eminent sense. It would provide time for passions to cool and allow Ehud Barak and Yasir Arafat to shore up their political bases. Above all, it would remove the artificial deadline of the end of President Clinton's term, which has been fueling the intensive negotiations and putting artificial pressure on both negotiating partners.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Max M. Kampelman's proposal (letter, Oct. 11) that we take a six-month recess in Middle East peace negotiations makes eminent sense. It would provide time for passions to cool and allow Ehud Barak and Yasir Arafat to shore up their political bases. Above all, it would remove the artificial deadline of the end of President Clinton's term, which has been fueling the intensive negotiations and putting artificial pressure on both negotiating partners.</p>
        <p>The White House should support such a proposal, if only for purely political reasons. Any blowup from forced negotiations would undoubtedly damage the election campaigns of Al Gore and Hillary Rodham Clinton.</p>
        <p>S. FRED SINGER  Fairfax, Va., Oct. 12, 2000</p>
      </block>
